<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06286108 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06286108 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Turkish military aircraft bombed five villages in northern Iraq Friday inrenewed cross-border raids apparently designed to punish Kurdish guerrillaswho killed 11 soldiers in southeastern Turkey four days ago. Iraqi Kurdishsources said at least three Iraqi Kurds died and 11 others -- includingcivilians -- were wounded in the attacks.;   The bombs were dropped on theremote, mountainous terrain near the Turkish border town of Cukurca, where theTurkish troops were killed. A Turkish official, however, denied that civilianswere wounded in Friday's raid. A high-ranking officer in the office of thechief of staff said the air raid concentrated on a valley 5 1/2 miles south ofthe border at a spot west of the Khabur River.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  KURDISH AREAS IN IRAQ BOMBED BY TURK PLANES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><TEXT>     In Ankara, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said, &quot;I approve (of) theoperation&quot; against the Kurdish Workers Party, or PKK, which has been waging anincreasingly violent war for Kurdish independence from Turkey. Since 1984, anestimated 3,000 people have been killed in violence related to the PKK'scampaign. The raid was the first Turkish cross-border strike since Aug. 8.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911012  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  185  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, October 12, 199100286108,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>